{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} {{Use British English|date=April 2014}} :''For the country estate of Holme Park at Sonning, see [[Reading Blue Coat School]]''
{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Holme Park | nickname = | image = | fullname = | location = [[Sonning]], [[England]] | coordinates = {{coord|51|28|0|N|0|55|5|W |region:GB_type:landmark |display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1939 | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = Grass | construction_cost = | architect = | former_names = | tenants = [[Reading R.F.C.|Reading RFC]] | capacity = | dimensions = }}
'''Holme Park''' is a sports ground in [[Sonning]] (occasionally called Sonning-on-Thames), a village and [[civil parish]] in the [[England|English]] county of [[Berkshire]], a few miles east of [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]]. It is used for [[rugby union]] matches and is the home of [[Reading R.F.C.|Reading Rugby Football Club]].
Reading RFC had a nomadic existence until, shortly before the [[World War II|Second World War]], the land at Holme Park was purchased and the pitches laid. After the war a new clubhouse and stand were erected, the stand later being moved to its present position on the far side of the ground. The current clubhouse was built through the efforts of Gordon Richens in 1968 and was expanded, with squash courts added, by Colin Barrett in 1975.
The club had been struggling with income over expenditure since the mid-1990s and with debts and loans spiralling the club found it increasing difficult to service the arrears.<ref>{{cite news | date=2005-01-20 | url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/11/11210/crisis_club_reading_plan_for_a_brave_new_world | title=Crisis club Reading plan for a brave new world | work=[[Reading Evening Post]] | accessdate=2008-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> An attempted buy-out of the club and assets by former coach Phil Hall was quashed at the club’s [[annual general meeting]] in 2007. [[Alastair McHarg]], capped 44&nbsp;times by Scotland, was a vociferous opponent of the Hall buy-out. He said "The good thing about the Phil Hall deal is that at least it has shaken up some people to get their act together."<ref>{{cite news | date=2007-05-11 | url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/s/2010625_rugby_hall_fails_in_his_bid_to_take_over_club | title=Hall fails in his bid to take over club | work=Reading Evening Post | accessdate=2008-01-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | date=2007-08-03 | url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/sport/2013/2013429/rugby_mchargs_60000_budget_to_survive_in_south_west_1 | title=McHarg’s £60,000 budget to survive in South West 1 | work=Reading Evening Post | accessdate=2008-01-06}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>
